#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:5
msgid "Emscripten Tutorial"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:7
msgid ""
"**Using Emscripten is, at a base level, fairly simple. This tutorial takes "
"you through the steps needed to compile your first Emscripten examples from "
"the command line. It also shows how to work with files and set the main "
"compiler optimization flags.**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:13
msgid "First things first"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:15
msgid ""
"Make sure you have :ref:`downloaded and installed <sdk-download-and-"
"install>` Emscripten (the exact approach for doing this will depend on your "
"operating system: Linux, Windows, or Mac)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:19
msgid ""
"Emscripten is accessed using the :ref:`emccdoc`. This script invokes all the "
"other tools needed to build your code, and can act as a drop-in replacement "
"for a standard compiler like *gcc* or *clang*. It is called on the command "
"line using ``./emcc`` or ``./em++``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:24
msgid ""
"On Windows the tool is called using the slightly different syntax: ``emcc`` "
"or ``em++``. The remainder of this tutorial uses the Linux approach (``./"
"emcc``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:28
msgid "For the next section you will need to open a command prompt:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:30
msgid "On Linux or macOS, open a *Terminal*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:31
msgid ""
"On Windows, open the :ref:`Emscripten Command Prompt <emcmdprompt>`, a "
"command prompt that has been pre-configured with the correct system paths "
"and settings to point to the :term:`active <Active Tool/SDK>` Emscripten "
"tools. To access this prompt, type **Emscripten** in the Windows start menu, "
"and then select the **Emscripten Command Prompt** option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:37
msgid ""
"Navigate with the command prompt to the emscripten directory under the SDK. "
"This is a folder below the :term:`emsdk root directory`, typically **<emsdk "
"root directory>/upstream/emscripten/**. The examples below will depend on "
"finding files relative to that location."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:42
msgid ""
"In older emscripten versions, the directory structure was different: the "
"version number appeared, and the backend (fastcomp/upstream) did not, so you "
"would use something like **<emsdk root directory>/emscripten/1.20.0/**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:48
msgid "Verifying Emscripten"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:50
msgid "If you haven't run Emscripten before, run it now with: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:54
msgid ""
"If the output contains warnings about missing tools, see :ref:`verifying-the-"
"emscripten-environment` for debugging help. Otherwise, continue to the next "
"sections where we'll build some code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:60
msgid "Running Emscripten"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:62
msgid "You can now compile your first C/C++ file to JavaScript."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:64
msgid ""
"First, let's have a look at the file to be compiled: **hello_world.c**. This "
"is the simplest test code in the SDK, and as you can see, all it does is "
"print \"hello, world!\" to the console and then exit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:72
msgid ""
"To build the JavaScript version of this code, simply specify the C/C++ file "
"after *emcc* (use *em++* to force compilation as C++): ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:78
msgid ""
"You should see two files generated by that command: **a.out.js** and **a.out."
"wasm**. The second is a WebAssembly file containing the compiled code, and "
"the first is a JavaScript file containing the runtime support to load and "
"execute it. You can run them using :term:`node.js`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:87
msgid "This prints \"hello, world!\" to the console, as expected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:89
msgid ""
"If an error occurs when calling *emcc*, run it with the ``-v`` option to "
"print out a lot of useful debug information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:92
msgid ""
"In this section, and later on, we run some files from the ``test/`` folder. "
"That folder contains files for the Emscripten test suite. Some can be run "
"standalone, but others must be run through the test harness itself, see :ref:"
"`emscripten-test-suite` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:100
msgid "Generating HTML"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:102
msgid ""
"Emscripten can also generate HTML for testing embedded JavaScript. To "
"generate HTML, use the ``-o`` (:ref:`output <emcc-o-target>`) command and "
"specify an html file as the target file: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:108
msgid "You can now open ``hello.html`` in a web browser."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:110
msgid ""
"Unfortunately, several browsers (including *Chrome* and *Safari*) do not "
"support ``file://`` :term:`XHR` requests, and can't load extra files needed "
"by the HTML (like a ``.wasm`` file, or packaged file data as mentioned lower "
"down). For these browsers, you'll need to serve the files using a :ref:"
"`local webserver <faq-local-webserver>` and then open ``http://"
"localhost:8000/hello.html``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:117
msgid ""
"Once you have the HTML loaded in your browser, you'll see a text area for "
"displaying the output of the ``printf()`` calls in the native code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:120
msgid ""
"The HTML output isn't limited just to just displaying text. You can also use "
"the SDL API to show a colored cube in a ``<canvas>`` element (on browsers "
"that support it). For an example, build the `hello_world_sdl.c <https://"
"github.com/emscripten-core/emscripten/blob/main/test/hello_world_sdl.c>`_ "
"test code and then refresh the browser: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:128
msgid "The source code for the second example is given below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:137
msgid "Using files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:139
msgid ""
"Your C/C++ code can access files using the normal libc stdio API (``fopen``, "
"``fclose``, etc.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:142
msgid ""
"JavaScript is usually run in the sandboxed environment of a web browser, "
"without direct access to the local file system. Emscripten simulates a file "
"system that you can access from your compiled C/C++ code using the normal "
"libc stdio API."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:146
msgid ""
"Files that you want to access should be :ref:`preloaded <emcc-preload-file>` "
"or :ref:`embedded <emcc-embed-file>` into the virtual file system. "
"Preloading (or embedding) generates a virtual file system that corresponds "
"to the file system structure at *compile* time, *relative to the current "
"directory*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:152
msgid ""
"The `hello_world_file.cpp <https://github.com/emscripten-core/emscripten/"
"blob/main/test/hello_world_file.cpp>`_ example shows how to load a file "
"(both the test code and the file to be loaded shown below):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:163
msgid ""
"The example expects to be able to load a file located at **test/"
"hello_world_file.txt**: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:167
msgid ""
"We compile the example from the directory \"above\" **test** to ensure the "
"virtual filesystem is created with the correct structure relative to the "
"compile-time directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:171
msgid ""
"The following command is used to specify a data file to :ref:`preload <emcc-"
"preload-file>` into Emscripten's virtual file system — before running any "
"compiled code. This approach is useful because Browsers can only load data "
"from the network asynchronously (except in Web Workers) while a lot of "
"native code uses synchronous file system access. Preloading ensures that the "
"asynchronous download of data files is complete (and the file is available) "
"before compiled code has the opportunity to access the Emscripten file "
"system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:184
msgid ""
"Run the above command, then open **hello.html** in a web browser to see the "
"data from **hello_world_file.txt** being displayed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:187
msgid ""
"For more information about working with the file system see the :ref:`file-"
"system-overview`, :ref:`Filesystem-API` and :ref:`Synchronous-virtual-XHR-"
"backed-file-system-usage`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:193
msgid "Optimizing code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:195
msgid ""
"Emscripten, like *gcc* and *clang*, generates unoptimized code by default. "
"You can generate :ref:`slightly-optimized <emcc-O1>` code with the ``-O1`` "
"command line argument: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:201
msgid ""
"The \"hello world\" code created in **a.out.js** doesn't really need to be "
"optimized, so you won't see a difference in speed when compared to the "
"unoptimized version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:205
msgid ""
"However, you can compare the generated code to see the differences. ``-O1`` "
"applies several minor optimizations and removes some runtime assertions. For "
"example, ``printf`` will have been replaced by ``puts`` in the generated "
"code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:209
msgid ""
"The optimizations provided by ``-O2`` (see :ref:`here <emcc-O2>`) are much "
"more aggressive. If you run the following command and inspect the generated "
"code (**a.out.js**) you will see that it looks very different: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:215
msgid ""
"For more information about compiler optimization options see :ref:"
"`Optimizing-Code` and the :ref:`emcc tool reference <emcc-compiler-"
"optimization-options>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:223
msgid "Emscripten Test Suite and Benchmarks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:225
msgid ""
"Emscripten has a comprehensive test suite, which covers virtually all "
"Emscripten functionality. These tests are an excellent resource for "
"developers as they provide practical examples of most features, and are "
"known to build successfully on the ``main`` branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:230
msgid "See :ref:`emscripten-test-suite` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:234
msgid "General tips and next steps"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:236
msgid ""
"This tutorial walked you through your first steps in calling Emscripten from "
"the command line. There is, of course, far more you can do with the tool. "
"Below are other general tips for using Emscripten:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:240
msgid ""
"This site has lots more information about :ref:`compiling and building "
"projects <compiling-and-running-projects-index>`, :ref:`integrating your "
"native code with the web environment <integrating-porting-index>`, :ref:"
"`packaging your code <packaging-code-index>` and publishing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:244
msgid ""
"The Emscripten test suite is a great place to look for examples of how to "
"use Emscripten. For example, if you want to better understand how the *emcc* "
"``--pre-js`` option works, search for ``--pre-js`` in the test suite: the "
"test suite is extensive and there are likely to be at least some examples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/getting_started/Tutorial.rst:248
msgid ""
"To learn how to use Emscripten in advanced ways, read :ref:`src/settings.js "
"<settings-js>` and :ref:`emcc <emccdoc>` which describe the compiler "
"options, and :ref:`emscripten-h` for details on JavaScript-specific C APIs "
"that your C/C++ programs can use when compiled with Emscripten."
msgstr ""

